chunks.text: Connector Issue Resolution Issue: When one tries to get data from MySQL in Power BI, the below error message pops up. “ This connector requires one or more additional components to be installed before it can be used ” Or “ Character set 'utf8mb3' is not supported by .Net Framework “

Scenario 1 (If you previously installed any latest version): Sometimes it might be due to the installation of the latest version of the connector like 8.0.30 or above. 1. Uninstall the latest version you have downloaded - To do it, double-click on the downloaded file of the connector it will give options like repair or uninstall. 2. Click on Uninstall and follow below scenario 2. Scenario 2 (install the missing connector): 1. install version 8.0.28 from: https://downloads.mysql.com/archives/c-net/ After you download it and run the file and during installation select the typical option. restart the computer. You should be good after that. 2. Make sure that you close the Power BI and restart the whole system for the changes to be applied Note Use TypicaI option while installing and 8.0.28 is the standard version as of now.

Scenario 3 (repair the connector): When you are not able to see the install option in the installer, then you need to proceed with this approach: Step 1: - Now click on Repair option Step 2: - It will take few seconds to repair and install necessary tools

Step 3: - Finally click on finish Step 4: - Now close the Power BI which is already opened and restart the system. Step 5: - Now open Power BI again and connect to MySQL Step 6: - Finally, you will get the option to connect the database

Q1 b) Describe Servlet Architecture in Detail (4 Marks) Ans: A Servlet is a Java program that runs on a web server and responds to client requests. Servlet Architecture Components 1. Client (Browser) Sends HTTP request (GET/POST). o 2. Web Server Receives request and forwards it to the servlet container. o 3. Servlet Container (e.g., Tomcat) Manages servlet life cycle. o Responsibilities: o Loading servlet  Creating servlet instance  Calling init(), service(), destroy()  Managing threads  Managing sessions and resources  4. Servlet Processes the request o Generates dynamic output (HTML/JSON/XML) o 5. Response Servlet sends response back → web server → browser. o Servlet Architecture Flow Client → Web Server → Servlet Container → Servlet → Response Servlet Life Cycle 1. init() – Called once when servlet loads 2. service() – Called for each request 3. destroy() – Called before servlet is removed Key Features Platform independent  Uses Java  Supports sessions, cookies  Efficient (multi-threaded) 

Q1 c) Explain DTD in XML with Schema, Elements & Attributes (9 Marks) Ans: 1. What is DTD? DTD = Document Type Definition It defines the structure and rules of an XML document. It tells: Which elements are allowed  Their order  Their attributes  What data they contain  DTD ensures the XML file is valid. 2. DTD Example XML File: <?xml version="1.0"?> <!DOCTYPE student SYSTEM "student.dtd"> <Student> <Name>Vijay</Name> <Roll>23</Roll> </Student> DTD File (student.dtd): <!ELEMENT Student (Name, Roll)> <!ELEMENT Name (#PCDATA)> <!ELEMENT Roll (#PCDATA)> 3. Elements in DTD An element is an XML tag. Syntax: <!ELEMENT tagname content>

Examples: (#PCDATA) = Parsed Character Data (text)  EMPTY = No content  ANY = Can contain anything  Example: <!ELEMENT Book (Title, Author)> 4. Attributes in DTD Attributes provide extra information to elements. Syntax: <!ATTLIST element attribute type value> Example: <!ATTLIST Student id CDATA #REQUIRED> Types: CDATA – normal text  ID – special unique id  #REQUIRED – must be present  #IMPLIED – optional  5. Internal vs External DTD Internal DTD Defined inside XML file. <!DOCTYPE Note [ <!ELEMENT Note (To, From)> ]> External DTD Defined in a separate file. <!DOCTYPE Note SYSTEM "note.dtd">

6. XML Schema (XSD) Schema is an improved version of DTD. Supports data types (int, string, date)  More powerful and flexible  Example: <xs:element name="age" type="xs:integer"/> OR Q2 a) What is Session? How cookies & URL rewriting are used for session management in Servlets? (9 Marks) Ans: 1. What is a Session? A session is a way to store user-specific data on the server for a limited time. When a user visits a website, a session ID is created.  This session ID is used to identify the same user across multiple  pages. Session helps in:  Login systems o Shopping carts o User preferences o Maintaining user activities o Session = Technique to remember the user until they leave or close the browser.

2. Session Management Using Cookies What are Cookies?  Small text files stored on the client’s browser.  Servlet uses cookies to store the session ID. How cookies manage session: 1. When a user first visits, server generates a session ID. 2. Server sends this session ID to browser in a cookie. 3. Browser sends this cookie back with each request. 4. Server reads the session ID → identifies the user. Example: Cookie c = new Cookie("sessionID", "12345"); res.addCookie(c); Advantages:  Automatic session tracking  Easy to implement Disadvantages:  User may disable cookies  Limited data can be stored 3. Session Management Using URL Rewriting What is URL rewriting? When cookies are disabled, session ID is added inside the URL itself. Example: http://example.com/home;jsessionid=ABC123 How it works: 1. Server generates session ID. 2. Session ID is appended with every URL the user clicks. 3. Server reads the ID from URL. 4. User session is maintained. Code Example: String url = res.encodeURL("home.jsp");

Q2 b) Write short notes on: AJAX & XML Transformation (9 Marks) Ans: i) AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) Meaning AJAX is a technique used to update a webpage without reloading the entire page. Full Form Asynchronous Java AScript and XML How AJAX Works 1. Browser creates an XMLHttpRequest object. 2. Sends request to server asynchronously. 3. Server processes and sends data only, not full page. 4. JavaScript updates only the required part of the page. Example var xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest(); xhttp.onload = function() { document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = this.responseText; } xhttp.open("GET", "data.txt", true); xhttp.send(); Advantages No page reload  Faster and smoother UI  Used in live search, chat apps, Gmail inbox refresh  Applications Form validation  Loading comments dynamically 

ii) XML Transformation Meaning XML Transformation means converting an XML document into: HTML  Another XML  Text  PDF (via tools)  This is done using XSLT (Extensible Stylesheet Language Transformations). Why needed? XML is for data storage  XSLT converts the raw XML into readable output  XSLT Components 1. XSL → stylesheet 2. XPath → selects XML nodes 3. Templates → describes how data should be displayed Example XML Vijay XSLT Example

Process 1. XML + XSLT = HTML output 2. Browser or processor applies the stylesheet 3. Final transformed document is shown to user

Q3 (a) Explain life cycle of JSP. Write advantages of JSP over Servlets. (9 Marks) Ans: A JSP (Java Server Page) is a web page that contains Java code + HTML. Its life cycle is the series of steps that happen from the moment a JSP is requested until it is destroyed. JSP Life Cycle 1. Translation Phase  The JSP file (.jsp) is converted into a Java Servlet file by the JSP engine.  Example: index.jsp → index_jsp.java. 2. Compilation Phase  The generated .java servlet file is compiled into a .class file.  Example: index_jsp.java → index_jsp.class. 3. Loading and Instantiation  The compiled servlet .class file is loaded into memory.  A JSP object/instance is created. 4. Initialization — jspInit()  The JSP container calls jspInit() only once.  It is used to write initialization code (like database connection). 5. Request Processing — _jspService()  For every request, _jspService(request, response) is executed.  This method: o Reads client input o Executes Java code inside the JSP o Generates the output HTML 6. Destruction — jspDestroy()  Method

Advantages of JSP over Servlet 1. Easier to Write JS P mixes HTML + Java easily.  In Servlet, writing HTML inside Java code becomes messy.  2. Q3 (b) Write short notes on: i) SOAP ii) WSDL(8 Marks) Ans: i) SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol) Concept in Brief SOAP is a protocol used to send messages between applications over the internet. It uses XML for data exchange. Explanation 1. SOAP is XML-based All data and messages are written in XML. o Platform-independent and language-independent. o 2. Uses Standard Internet Protocols Mostly uses HTTP o Can also use SMTP or other protocols. o 3. SOAP Structure A SOAP message has: Envelope → root element o Header → optional information o Body → main message o Fault → error details o 4. Highly Secure & Reliable Supports WS-Security standards. o Used in banking, telecom, enterprise applications. o 5. Interoperable Any system (Java, .NET, Python) can communicate using SOAP. o ii) WSDL (Web Services Description Language) Concept in Brief WSDL is an XML document that describes what a web service does and how to use it.

ActionServlet (Controller)  It is the main controller of the ap plication.  Receives all requests from users.  Reads configuration from struts-config.xml.  Calls the appropriate Action class. 2. ActionForm (Form Bean)  Java class used to capture user input from JSP.  Validates the input.  Example: LoginForm, RegisterForm. 3. JSP Pages (View)  Used for displaying UI.  They show results received from Action classes. 📍 Flow of Struts Application 1. User sends request → goes to ActionServlet. 2. Q4 (b) Explain JSP support for MVC (Model–View–Controller) for developing web applications.(8) Ans: MVC is a design pattern that separates user interface, data, and logic. JSP is mainly used as View, but it supports all MVC components. MVC Components Using JSP 1. Model (Data + Business Logic)  Model = JavaBeans, POJO classes, Database code.  Handles: o Data processing o Database transactions o Application logic  JSP interacts with Model using: o JSTL o EL (Expression Language) o <jsp:useBean> tag 2. View (User Interface) — JSP  JSP acts as View.  Displays output from the Model.  Uses: o HTML o CSS o JavaBeans o JSP EL and JSTL  Does not contain business logic. 3. Controller (Servlet)  Servlet acts as the Controller.  Controller tasks: o Accepts user request o Calls the correct Model components o Stores results in request/session o Forwards to JSP (View) Uses RequestDispatcher: request.getRequestDispatcher("result.jsp").forward(request, response);

How JSP Fits into MVC Flow Step-by- Step MVC Flow 1. User sends request (e.g., login). 2. Request goes to Servlet (Controller). 3. Servlet calls Model to process the request. 4. Model returns data/results. 5. Servlet forwards result to the JSP page (View). 6. JSP shows the data to the user. Benefits of Using JSP in MVC Clear separation of roles  Easy maintenance  JSP contains only UI → cleaner code  Servlet handles logic → improved performance  Model stores data → reusable classes  @TheVijayAcademy

Q6 b) Explain functions in PHP with example & session management.[9] Ans: Functions are reusable blocks of code. Session management stores user data across multiple web pages. Functions in PHP (with example) Definition A function is a block of statements that performs a specific task and can be reused. Syntax function functionName(parameters) { // statements } Example function add($a, $b){ return $a + $b; } echo add(10, 20); // Output: 30 Benefits Reusability  Easy debugging  Code modularity  Better readability  Session Management in PHP What is a Session? Starting a Session session_start(); Storing Data in Session $_SESSION['username'] = "Vijay"; Accessing Session Data echo $_SESSION['username']; Destroying Session session_destroy(); Q7 (a) Explain classes and objects in Ruby with appropriate examples. [9] Ans: In Ruby, everything is an object, and objects are created from classes. A class is a blueprint, while an object is a real instance created from that blueprint. 1. Class in Ruby A class groups together: Data (variables)  Behaviour (methods)  @TheVijayAcademy

Syntax of a class class ClassName # variables and methods end 2. Creating an object Objects are created using the .new method. obj = ClassName.new Example: Simple Ruby Class & Object class Student def initialize(name, marks) @name = name @marks = marks end def display puts "Name: #{@name}" puts "Marks: #{@marks}" end end # Creating objects s1 = Student.new("Ravi", 85) s2 = Student.new("Anita", 90) s1.display s2.display Explanation initialize → constructor, runs automatically when object created  @name and @marks → instance variables  display → method  Student.new → creates objects  This is how Ruby uses classes and objects to organize code in an OOP way.

Q7 (b) Introduce the concept of Rails application. Describe layouts & stylesheet in Rails. [8] Ans: 1. Concept of Rails Application Ruby on Rails is a web application framework based on: MVC (Model–View–Controller)  Convention over Configuration  DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)  A Rails application contains: Models → handle database logic  Views → HTML pages seen by user  Controllers → connect models & views  Routes → decide URL paths  Assets → CSS, JS, images  Rails helps to quickly build dynamic, database-driven websites. 2. Layouts in Rails A layout is like a master template used for common design across pages. Example: header, footer, navbar, sidebar. Default layout file: app/views/layouts/application.html.erb This file contains: @TheVijayAcademy

<!DOCTYPE html> <html> <head> <title>MyApp</title> <%= csrf_meta_tags %> <%= csp_meta_tag %> <%= stylesheet_link_tag "application" %> </head> <body> <%= yield %> <!-- Page content goes here --> </body> </html> yield → inserts the page’s actual content  Prevents repeating same HTML on every page  3. Stylesheets in Rails Rails uses the asset pipeline to manage CSS. Stylesheets are stored in: app/assets/stylesheets/ Example file: application.css You include it in layout using: <%= stylesheet_link_tag "application" %> You can add your own CSS files: app/assets/stylesheets/home.css Rails compiles and optimizes all CSS before sending to the browser. @TheVijayAcademy

Integer Whole numbers Operations: +, -, *, /, %, ** Example: a = 10 b = 3 puts a + b puts a % b 2. Float Decimal numbers Example: x = 5.5 y = 2.0 puts x / y 3. String Sequence of characters Operations: Concatenation: "Hello" + " World"  Repetition: "Hi" * 3  Length: "Ruby".length  Example: name = "Ruby" puts name.upcase

4. Boolean true or false Used in conditions. 5. Nil Represents "nothing" or "no value". 6. Pattern Matching (Regular Expressions) Used using /pattern/. Example: puts "hello" =~ /he/ # returns index 0 Q8 (b) Explain Architecture of EJB & explain types of EJB in detail. [9] Ans: What is EJB? EJB (Enterprise JavaBean) is a server-side component used to develop: Large-scale  Secure  Transaction-based  applications in Java. Architecture of EJB EJB architecture has three main parts: 1. Client Layer User interface or application that calls EJB. @TheVijayAcademy

2. EJB Container Runs on application server. Provides:  Sec urity Transactions  Life-cycle management  Object pooling  3. EJB Server The actual application server (JBoss, GlassFish, WebLogic). Types of EJB 1. Session Beans Perform business logic. a) Stateless Session Bean Does not store client data  Example: login check, calculations  b) Stateful Session Bean Stores data of one client session  Example: shopping cart  c) Singleton Session Bean Only one instance in entire application  Example: configuration, logs  2. Message-Driven Beans (MDB) Used for asynchronous communication. Works with JMS (Java Messaging Service). Example: sending notifications, processing messages in queue. @TheVijayAcademy
